# React Compiler

## Rules

- **React Compiler is enabled in this project.** It automatically memoizes components, hooks, and expressions. You do not need to manually optimize re-renders in most cases.
- **Do not use `React.memo()`.** The compiler handles component memoization automatically. Wrapping components in `React.memo()` is redundant and adds unnecessary code.
- **Do not use `useMemo()`.** The compiler detects expensive computations and memoizes them automatically. Manual `useMemo()` calls are unnecessary.
- **Do not use `useCallback()`.** The compiler automatically memoizes callback functions passed as props. Manual `useCallback()` calls are unnecessary.
- **Components must be pure.** The compiler assumes components are pure functions of their props and state. A component must return the same JSX for the same props and state. Side effects must live in `useEffect` or event handlers, not in the render body.
- **Use `"use no memo"` directive sparingly.** If the compiler causes issues with a specific component or hook (rare), you can add `"use no memo"` at the top of the function to opt it out. This should be a last resort with a comment explaining why.
- **Do not read or mutate refs during render.** Ref reads/writes must happen in effects or event handlers, never in the component body. The compiler cannot optimize code that reads mutable refs during render.
- **Follow the Rules of React strictly.** The compiler enforces purity, idempotency, and the rules of hooks more strictly than runtime React. Violations may cause incorrect memoization.

## Examples

### Good

```typescript
// Simple component - compiler handles memoization
export const UserCard = ({ user, onSelect }: TUserCardProps) => {
  const { t } = useTranslation();

  // Compiler auto-memoizes this computation
  const fullName = `${user.firstName} ${user.lastName}`;

  // Compiler auto-memoizes this callback
  const handleClick = () => {
    onSelect(user.id);
  };

  return (
    <Card onClick={handleClick}>
      <CardTitle>{fullName}</CardTitle>
      <Badge>{t(`roles.${user.role}`)}</Badge>
    </Card>
  );
};

// Derived data - compiler handles memoization
export const UserList = ({ users, filter }: TUserListProps) => {
  // Compiler auto-memoizes this filter operation
  const filteredUsers = users.filter((u) => u.role === filter);

  return (
    <div>
      {filteredUsers.map((user) => (
        <UserCard key={user.id} user={user} />
      ))}
    </div>
  );
};

// Opting out (rare, with explanation)
export const AnimationComponent = () => {
  "use no memo"; // Compiler conflicts with the animation library's mutable state

  // ... component code
};
```

### Bad

```typescript
// Unnecessary React.memo
export const UserCard = React.memo(({ user }: TUserCardProps) => {
  return <Card>{user.name}</Card>;
});

// Unnecessary useMemo
const filteredUsers = useMemo(
  () => users.filter((u) => u.role === filter),
  [users, filter]
);

// Unnecessary useCallback
const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
  onSelect(user.id);
}, [onSelect, user.id]);

// Impure component (side effect in render)
export const Counter = ({ count }: TCounterProps) => {
  document.title = `Count: ${count}`; // Side effect in render body
  return <span>{count}</span>;
};

// Reading ref during render
export const MeasuredBox = () => {
  const ref = useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null);
  const width = ref.current?.offsetWidth ?? 0; // Ref read during render
  return <div ref={ref}>{width}px</div>;
};

// Overusing "use no memo"
export const SimpleButton = () => {
  "use no memo"; // No justification - don't opt out without reason
  return <Button>Click</Button>;
};
```
